mshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cunliffe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place in Lancashire, near Rishton, recorded in 1246 as <i>Kunteclive</i>, from Old English <i>cunte</i> ‘cunt’ + <i>clif</i> ‘slope’, i.e. ‘slope with a slit or crack in it’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cundiff","meanings":["English (Cheshire): variant of   Cunliffe  ."]},{"name":"Conliffe","meanings":["English: variant of   Cunliffe  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Cunliffe was born in 1490, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Thomas Tilley in 1509, in Henlow, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died on 24 November 1556, in her hometown, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1490–24 November 1556":"1490–24. november 1556","1490–1556":"1490–1556","1510–1582":"1510–1582","1515–1579":"1515–1579","1579":"1579","1556":"1556","1510":"1510","about 1510":"umbes 1510","24 November 1556":"24. november 1556","1582":"1582","1509":"1509","1490":"1490","1515":"1515","Henlow, Central Bedfordshire Unitary Authority, Bedfordshire, England":"Henlow, Bedfordshire, England","nottingham, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Henlow, Bedfordshire, , England":"Henlow, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Henlow, Bedfordshire, England":"Henlow, Bedfordshire, England","Nottingham, Bedfordshire, England, united Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1490–24 November 1556":"1490–24. marraskuuta 1556","1490–1556":"1490–1556"